{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58009d41-583c-4267-a970-5f394c2c0ca4","content":"Use `dotnet watch` to automatically re-run tests on file save:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThis watches for file changes and re-runs the filtered test automatically. No extra setup needed — your project already targets .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n**Quick note on the failing test:** `RemoveStock` never validates quantity — it just subtracts without throwing. You'll need to add a bounds check in `RemoveStock` to make that test pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eb8d2399-4286-4008-b57d-ed77b6823d8e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for iterating on test fixes. Since they're using .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me suggest using `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests automatically when files change. That's the standard hot-reload approach for .NET test projects.\n\nActually, with `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` runner specified in global.json, they might be able to use `dotnet test --hotreload` directly. But `dotnet watch test` is the more established approach.\n\n\nI should just recommend the approach rather than implementing it for them since they're asking how to set it up.","outputTokens":309},"id":"458d695f-cb54-4023-b718-5b66aee53cf4","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:43:42.191Z","parentId":"0d0c6da5-fc49-4be8-976a-7340228c97e0"}
